<p>The â€œtoo soonâ€ argument against a reappearance of the Joker character, so soon after Heath Ledgerâ€™s death, is an appeal to ethos. Jokes about Michael Jackson in ordinary settings during the course of our daily lives are still often met with â€œtoo soon.â€ There is often a comic element to this â€œtoo soonâ€ response, but, an element of respect for the deceased underlies the sentiment that it is in fact â€œtoo soonâ€ to joke about the dead. Following from this, it is logical to conclude that if, out of respect for the man, we can not yet joke about Heath Ledger, then, out of the same respect for the actor, the Joker (Ledgerâ€™s masterpiece) should be laid to rest with Heath Ledger â€” out of respect.Â </p>

<p>The reason that this argument does not hold up is because the American culture and Hollywood do not operate under anything that resembles an ideal respect. We always had the sense that the people in Hollywood are debasing people, and now, through the <a href="http://www.theverge.com/2014/12/12/7384871/why-were-reporting-on-sony-leak-hack-ethics-mpaa">e-mails leaked by the hacks on SONY</a>, we have certainty that this is indeed the case.Â What I just said is harsh and a generalization, so I want you to take it for what it is: the respect necessary to enforce the â€œtoo soonâ€ argument as a realistic argument does not exist in Hollywood.Â Neither does this type of respect exist in American culture.Â We are a nation of addicts, constantly anticipating and demanding the â€œnext big thing.â€Â (Or the next <a href="http://www.thehighscreen.com/2014/10/jennifer-lawrence-vanity-fair-hates/">nude photo scandal from ourÂ <em>beloved</em> entertainers</a>.)Â We do not have time to place flowers beneath the epitaphs of our past entertainers.Â We are going, going, gone on to Expendables 3, 4, 5, ad infinitum.Â A reliance on respect for the basis of our â€œtoo soonâ€ argument is not naive at all, but it is flat out too spartan for the America we live in.</p>

<p>Before I move on to the argument that will, I hope, negate the â€œtoo soonâ€ argument all together, I want to comment on what gave Heath Ledgerâ€™s Joker the power that it continues to have over our society. Ledger accomplished what is the greatest aspiration of an artist in any medium: to disappear behind his art.Â This goal, while not easy for any artist, is perhaps most difficult for an actor to succeed in doing.Â Unlike any other artist, the actorâ€™s physical being is always one with the physical medium of his art. A painter is present within all of the frames that house his art, but she might be smoking a cigarette at a nearby cafe while an audience gathers to study her work.Â A writer throws her consciousness into her text, but she is not within the steam that rises from the cup of coffee on the desk beside the reader, nor is she hiding like a fly in the lampshade, from where a dim orange light rustles over each page.Â An actor can not disengage from her material like other artists can, except perhaps psychically.Â (I imagine that this psychic effort is grueling, and that it demands tenacious self-discipline).Â </p>

