<p>Nolanâ€™s Batman trilogy, especially <em>Batman BeginsÂ _and _The Dark Knight</em>, placed supermen in our world; their settings are familiar, the dialogue is contemporary and natural.Â Christian Baleâ€™s Batman felt more real to us than did Tom Wilkinsonâ€™s crime lord Carmine Falcone, because Batman expresses our desire for justice, whereas Falcone confronted us with the too real reality that there are malevolent people in this world who kill off the best of us for greedy intentions.Â The argument for justice may soon fail us for the same reason that the â€œtoo soonâ€ argument failed us.Â The failure of our legal system to indict the officer who strangled Eric Garner to death may be a foreboding that justice itself is too ideal of a concept for the America we live in.</p>

<p>Instead of the narrative that prevails in Executive speeches and in the narrative of our educational systems of â€œa country by the people for the people,â€ an Us vs. Them relationship between the American government and the American people has come to define Americaâ€™s political and social reality.Â There is a popular mistrust of our political institutions, which has given way, in some cases, to hostility toward these institutions.Â Heath Ledgerâ€™s Joker is a radical champion of this mistrust and hostility, but the Joker is not a reformer: he is an anarchist and anarchy is no solution at all.Â Heath Ledgerâ€™s Joker, the anarchist, combined with his emergence into a world so familiar to our own, is what gives his character the power and relevance that it has over our culture. His presence anticipates the annihilation of what is familiar to us.Â </p>

